cted to the rectum and also called a mucous fistula, drains small amounts of mucus material. This is most often a temporary colostomy performed to rest an area of bowel, and to be later closed.}{\f1\fs28\cf1\insrsid337484\charrsid15666328 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\intbl\faauto\rin0\lin0\pararsid132171\yts15 {\b\fs28\ul\kerning36\insrsid337484\charrsid15666328 Care of colostomies}{\b\fs28\ul\kerning36\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 
\par Immediate post operative
\par General
\par }{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 1.Monitor vital signs every 15 minutes until patient is awake then 30 minutes until patient gets to the ward then every 4 hours
\par 2. IV fluids (NS and Dextrose) at least 500mls every 6 hours
\par 3.Continue prophylactic antibiotics
\par 4. Analgesia- 1mg/kg of pethidine then introduce IM NSAIDs as decrease pethidine dose. 
\par 5.Keep patient }{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 nil}{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328  per oral
\par 6. Keep input and output chart thus keep NG tube, and urethral catheter.
\par }{\b\fs28\ul\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 Stoma management}{\b\fs28\ul\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 .
\par }{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 1.The patient is instructed how to support the operative site duri}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 ng deep breathing and coughing
\par 2. The stoma }{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 is observed for color and amount of wound }{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 drainage. Initially, the colostomy will drai}{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 n bloody mucus}{
\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 .
\par 3. Fluids}{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328  and electrolytes are infused intravenously until the patient's diet is can gradually be resumed, beginning with liquids}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328  with the return of bowel sounds.
\par }{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 Usually within 72 hours, passage of gas and stool through the stoma begins. Initially the stool is liquid, gradually thickening as the patient begins to take solid foods. }{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 

\par }{\fs28\insrsid132171\charrsid15666328 The patient is usually out of bed in 8\endash 24 hours after surgery and discharged in 2\endash 4 days.
\par }{\fs28\insrsid3670290\charrsid15666328 4. C}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 ounseling
\par All patients should be counseled about colostomy before surgery and counseling and education continued after the surgery both within the ward and even after discharge.
\par The counseling should also include the spouse and the family members to ensure support of the patient and to continue his usual lifestyle.
\par 5.Education
\par During the hospital stay, the patient and his or her caregivers will be educated on how to care for the colostomy. 
\par i)-Determination of appropriate pouching supplies
\par }{\fs28\insrsid4468810\charrsid15666328 ii)P}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 roper application of the pouch }{\fs28\insrsid4468810\charrsid15666328 o}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 n the stoma to avoid leakage
\par ii)}{\fs28\insrsid3670290\charrsid15666328 S}{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 chedule of how often to change the pouch 
\par iii)}{\fs28\insrsid4468810\charrsid15666328  }{\fs28\insrsid1313566\charrsid15666328 Regular assessment and meticulous care of the skin.
\par }{\fs28\insrsid4468810\charrsid15666328 iv) diet changes
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\intbl\faauto\rin0\lin0\pararsid14642540\yts15 {\fs28\insrsid4468810\charrsid15666328 v)counseling on regular activities and work}{\fs28\insrsid14642540\charrsid15666328 
